ledging their foreign derivation.The book reveals how artefacts began to signify as vernacular idioms in the first place, often through obscuring their non-local origin and tainting subsequent discussions of the imagined purity of national culture as a result.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aDESIGN / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aInvented tradition.  aPoland-Lithuania.  aSarmatia.  acarpets.  acultural distinctiveness.  ademi-orientalism.  aentangled history.  afashion.  aillustrated histories.  amaps.  anativism.  atransculturation.1 aGrusiecki, Tomasz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616437740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526164377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526164377/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023